# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: watchdog-timer-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] In engineering, a **fail-safe** is a design feature or practice that, in the event of a failure of the design feature, inherently responds in a way that will cause minimal or no harm to other equipment, to the environment or to people.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] Unlike inherent safety to a particular hazard, a system being "fail-safe" does not mean that failure is naturally inconsequential, but rather that the system's design prevents or mitigates unsafe consequences of the system's failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] If and when a "fail-safe" system fails, it remains at least as safe as it was before the failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] Since many types of failure are possible, failure mode and effects analysis is used to examine failure situations and recommend safety design and procedures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] Some systems can never be made fail-safe, as continuous availability is needed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] Redundancy, fault tolerance, or contingency plans are used for these situations (e.g. multiple independently controlled and fuel-fed engines).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] As well as physical devices and systems fail-safe procedures can be created so that if a procedure is not carried out or carried out incorrectly no dangerous action results.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] Fail-safe (foolproof) devices are also known as *poka-yoke* devices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] *Poka-yoke*, a Japanese term, was coined by Shigeo Shingo, a quality expert.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] The opposite of *fail-closed* is called *fail-open*.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] Fail active operational can be installed on systems that have a high degree of redundancy so that a single failure of any part of the system can be tolerated (fail active operational) and a second failure can be detected – at which point the system will turn itself off (uncouple, fail passive).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] One way of accomplishing this is to have three identical systems installed, and a control logic which detects discrepancies.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] An example for this are many aircraft systems, among them inertial navigation systems and pitot tubes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] During the Cold War, "failsafe point" was the term used for the point of no return for American Strategic Air Command nuclear bombers, just outside Soviet airspace.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] In the event of receiving an attack order, the bombers were required to linger at the failsafe point and wait for a second confirming order; until one was received, they would not arm their bombs or proceed further.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] The design was to prevent any single failure of the American command system causing nuclear war.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fail-safe] This sense of the term entered the American popular lexicon with the publishing of the 1962 novel *Fail-Safe*.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A **microcontroller** (**MC**, **uC**, or **μC**) or **microcontroller unit** (**MCU**) is a small computer on a single integrated circuit.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A microcontroller contains one or more processor cores along with memory and programmable input/output peripherals.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Program memory in the form of NOR flash, OTP ROM, or ferroelectric RAM is also often included on the chip, as well as a small amount of RAM.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are designed for embedded applications, in contrast to the microprocessors used in personal computers or other general-purpose applications consisting of various discrete chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In modern terminology, a microcontroller is similar to, but less sophisticated than, a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A SoC may include a microcontroller as one of its components but usually integrates it with advanced peripherals like a graphics processing unit (GPU), a Wi-Fi module, or one or more coprocessors.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are used in automatically controlled products and devices, such as automobile engine control systems, implantable medical devices, remote controls, office machines, appliances, power tools, toys, and other embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] By reducing the size and cost compared to a design that uses a separate microprocessor, memory, and input/output devices, microcontrollers make digital control of more devices and processes practical.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Mixed-signal microcontrollers are common, integrating analog components needed to control non-digital electronic systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In the context of the Internet of things, microcontrollers are an economical and popular means of data collection, sensing and actuating the physical world as edge devices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers may use four-bit words and operate at frequencies as low as 4 kHz for low power consumption (single-digit milliwatts or microwatts).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] They generally have the ability to retain functionality while waiting for an event such as a button press or other interrupt; power consumption while sleeping (with the CPU clock and most peripherals off) may be just nanowatts, making many of them well suited for long lasting battery applications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Other microcontrollers may serve performance-critical roles, where they may need to act more like a digital signal processor (DSP), with higher clock speeds and power consumption.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released on a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] It was followed by the 4-bit Intel 4040, the 8-bit Intel 8008, and the 8-bit Intel 8080.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] All of these processors required several external chips to implement a working system, including memory and peripheral interface chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] As a result, the total system cost was several hundred (1970s US) dollars, making it impossible to economically computerize small appliances.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] MOS Technology introduced its sub-$100 microprocessors in 1975, the 6501 and 6502.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Their chief aim was to reduce this cost barrier but these microprocessors still required external support, memory, and peripheral chips which kept the total system cost in the hundreds of dollars.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] One book credits TI engineers Gary Boone and Michael Cochran with the successful creation of the first microcontroller in 1971.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The result of their work was the TMS 1000, which became commercially available in 1974.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] It combined read-only memory, read/write memory, processor and clock on one chip and was targeted at embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] During the early-to-mid-1970s, Japanese electronics manufacturers began producing microcontrollers for automobiles, including 4-bit MCUs for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, and dashboard, and 8-bit MCUs for engine control.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Partly in response to the existence of the single-chip TMS 1000, Intel developed a computer system on a chip optimized for control applications, the Intel 8048, with commercial parts first shipping in 1977.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] It combined RAM and ROM on the same chip with a microprocessor.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Among numerous applications, this chip would eventually find its way into over one billion PC keyboards.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Valenter, stated that the microcontroller was one of the most successful products in the company's history, and he expanded the microcontroller division's budget by over 25%.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Most microcontrollers at this time had concurrent variants.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] One had EPROM program memory, with a transparent quartz window in the lid of the package to allow it to be erased by exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] These erasable chips were often used for prototyping.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The other variant was either a mask-programmed ROM or a PROM variant which was only programmable once.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] For the latter, sometimes the designation *OTP* was used, standing for "one-time programmable".
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In an OTP microcontroller, the PROM was usually of identical type as the EPROM, but the chip package had no quartz window; because there was no way to expose the EPROM to ultraviolet light, it could not be erased.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Because the erasable versions required ceramic packages with quartz windows, they were significantly more expensive than the OTP versions, which could be made in lower-cost opaque plastic packages.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] For the erasable variants, quartz was required, instead of less expensive glass, for its transparency to ultraviolet light—to which glass is largely opaque—but the main cost differentiator was the ceramic package itself.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] **Piggyback microcontrollers** were also used.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In 1993, the introduction of EEPROM memory allowed microcontrollers (beginning with the Microchip PIC16C84) to be electrically erased quickly without an expensive package as required for EPROM, allowing both rapid prototyping, and in-system programming.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] (EEPROM technology had been available prior to this time, but the earlier EEPROM was more expensive and less durable, making it unsuitable for low-cost mass-produced microcontrollers.) The same year, Atmel introduced the first microcontroller using Flash memory, a special type of EEPROM.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Other companies rapidly followed suit, with both memory types.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Nowadays microcontrollers are cheap and readily available for hobbyists, with large online communities around certain processors.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In 2002, about 55% of all CPUs sold in the world were 8-bit microcontrollers and microprocessors.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Over two billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 1997, and according to Semico, over four billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 2006.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] More recently, Semico has claimed the MCU market grew 36.5% in 2010 and 12% in 2011.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A typical home in a developed country is likely to have only four general-purpose microprocessors but around three dozen microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A typical mid-range automobile has about 30 microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] They can also be found in many electrical devices such as washing machines, microwave ovens, and telephones.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Cost to manufacture can be under US$0.10 per unit.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Cost has plummeted over time, with the cheapest 8-bit microcontrollers being available for under US$0.03 in 2018, and some 32-bit microcontrollers around US$1 for similar quantities.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In 2012, following a global crisis—a worst ever annual sales decline and recovery and average sales price year-over-year plunging 17%—the biggest reduction since the 1980s—the average price for a microcontroller was US$0.88 (US$0.69 for 4-/8-bit, US$0.59 for 16-bit, US$1.76 for 32-bit).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In 2012, worldwide sales of 8-bit microcontrollers were around US$4 billion, while 4-bit microcontrollers also saw significant sales.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] On 21 June 2018, the "world's smallest computer" was announced by the University of Michigan.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Because they are too small to have conventional radio antennae, they receive and transmit data with visible light.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A microcontroller can be considered a self-contained system with a processor, memory and peripherals and can be used as an embedded system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The majority of microcontrollers in use today are embedded in other machinery, such as automobiles, telephones, appliances, and peripherals for computer systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] While some embedded systems are very sophisticated, many have minimal requirements for memory and program length, with no operating system, and low software complexity.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Typical input and output devices include switches, relays, solenoids, LEDs, small or custom liquid-crystal displays, radio frequency devices, and sensors for data such as temperature, humidity, light level etc.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Embedded systems usually have no keyboard, screen, disks, printers, or other recognizable I/O devices of a personal computer, and may lack human interaction devices of any kind.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers must provide real-time (predictable, though not necessarily fast) response to events in the embedded system they are controlling.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Possible interrupt sources are device-dependent and often include events such as an internal timer overflow, completing an analog-to-digital conversion, a logic-level change on an input such as from a button being pressed, and data received on a communication link.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Where power consumption is important as in battery devices, interrupts may also wake a microcontroller from a low-power sleep state where the processor is halted until required to do something by a peripheral event.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Typically microcontroller programs must fit in the available on-chip memory, since it would be costly to provide a system with external, expandable memory.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Compilers and assemblers are used to convert both high-level and assembly language code into a compact machine code for storage in the microcontroller's memory.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Depending on the device, the program memory may be permanent, read-only memory that can only be programmed at the factory, or it may be field-alterable flash or erasable read-only memory.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Manufacturers have often produced special versions of their microcontrollers in order to help the hardware and software development of the target system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Originally these included EPROM versions that have a "window" on the top of the device through which program memory can be erased by ultraviolet light, ready for reprogramming after a programming ("burn") and test cycle.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Since 1998, EPROM versions are rare and have been replaced by EEPROM and flash, which are easier to use (can be erased electronically) and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Other versions may be available where the ROM is accessed as an external device rather than as internal memory, however these are becoming rare due to the widespread availability of cheap microcontroller programmers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The use of field-programmable devices on a microcontroller may allow field update of the firmware or permit late factory revisions to products that have been assembled but not yet shipped.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Programmable memory also reduces the lead time required for deployment of a new product.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Where hundreds of thousands of identical devices are required, using parts programmed at the time of manufacture can be economical.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] These "mask-programmed" parts have the program laid down in the same way as the logic of the chip, at the same time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A customized microcontroller incorporates a block of digital logic that can be personalized for additional processing capability, peripherals and interfaces that are adapted to the requirements of the application.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers usually contain from several to dozens of general purpose input/output pins (GPIO).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] GPIO pins are software configurable to either an input or an output state.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] When GPIO pins are configured to an input state, they are often used to read sensors or external signals.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Configured to the output state, GPIO pins can drive external devices such as LEDs or motors, often indirectly, through external power electronics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Many embedded systems need to read sensors that produce analog signals.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] However, because they are built to interpret and process digital data, i.e.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] 1s and 0s, they are not able to do anything with the analog signals that may be sent to it by a device.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] So, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is used to convert the incoming data into a form that the processor can recognize.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A less common feature on some microcontrollers is a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that allows the processor to output analog signals or voltage levels.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In addition to the converters, many embedded microprocessors include a variety of timers as well.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] One of the most common types of timers is the programmable interval timer (PIT).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A PIT may either count down from some value to zero, or up to the capacity of the count register, overflowing to zero.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Once it reaches zero, it sends an interrupt to the processor indicating that it has finished counting.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] This is useful for devices such as thermostats, which periodically test the temperature around them to see if they need to turn the air conditioner on/off, the heater on/off, etc.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A dedicated pulse-width modulation (PWM) block makes it possible for the CPU to control power converters, resistive loads, motors, etc., without using many CPU resources in tight timer loops.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A universal asynchronous receiver/transmitter (UART) block makes it possible to receive and transmit data over a serial line with very little load on the CPU.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Dedicated on-chip hardware also often includes capabilities to communicate with other devices (chips) in digital formats such as Inter-Integrated Circuit (I²C), Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI), Universal Serial Bus (USB), and Ethernet.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers may not implement an external address or data bus as they integrate RAM and non-volatile memory on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Using fewer pins, the chip can be placed in a much smaller, cheaper package.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Integrating the memory and other peripherals on a single chip and testing them as a unit increases the cost of that chip, but often results in decreased net cost of the embedded system as a whole.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] This integration drastically reduces the number of chips and the amount of wiring and circuit board space that would be needed to produce equivalent systems using separate chips.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Furthermore, on low pin count devices in particular, each pin may interface to several internal peripherals, with the pin function selected by software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] This allows a part to be used in a wider variety of applications than if pins had dedicated functions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers have proved to be highly popular in embedded systems since their introduction in the 1970s.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers use a Harvard architecture: separate memory buses for instructions and data, allowing accesses to take place concurrently.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Where a Harvard architecture is used, instruction words for the processor may be a different bit size than the length of internal memory and registers; for example: 12-bit instructions used with 8-bit data registers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The decision of which peripheral to integrate is often difficult.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The microcontroller vendors often trade operating frequencies and system design flexibility against time-to-market requirements from their customers and overall lower system cost.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Manufacturers have to balance the need to minimize the chip size against additional functionality.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontroller architectures vary widely.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Some designs include general-purpose microprocessor cores, with one or more ROM, RAM, or I/O functions integrated onto the package.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Other designs are purpose-built for control applications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A microcontroller instruction set usually has many instructions intended for bit manipulation (bit-wise operations) to make control programs more compact.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] For example, a general-purpose processor might require several instructions to test a bit in a register and branch if the bit is set, where a microcontroller could have a single instruction to provide that commonly required function.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers historically have not had math coprocessors, so floating-point arithmetic has been performed by software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] However, some recent designs do include FPUs and DSP-optimized features.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] An example would be Microchip's PIC32 MIPS-based line.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers were originally programmed only in assembly language, but various high-level programming languages, such as C, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Compilers for general-purpose languages will typically have some restrictions as well as enhancements to better support the unique characteristics of microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers have environments to aid developing certain types of applications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontroller vendors often make tools freely available to make it easier to adopt their hardware.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Microcontrollers with specialty hardware may require their own non-standard dialects of C, such as SDCC for the 8051, which prevent using standard tools (such as code libraries or static analysis tools) even for code unrelated to hardware features.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Interpreters may also contain nonstandard features, such as MicroPython, although a fork, CircuitPython, has looked to move hardware dependencies to libraries and have the language adhere to a more CPython standard.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Interpreter firmware is also available for some microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] For example, BASIC on the early microcontroller Intel 8052; BASIC and FORTH on the Zilog Z8 as well as some modern devices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Typically these interpreters support interactive programming.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Simulators are available for some microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] These allow a developer to analyze what the behavior of the microcontroller and their program should be if they were using the actual part.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A simulator will show the internal processor state and also that of the outputs, as well as allowing input signals to be generated.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] While on the one hand most simulators will be limited from being unable to simulate much other hardware in a system, they can exercise conditions that may otherwise be hard to reproduce at will in the physical implementation, and can be the quickest way to debug and analyze problems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Recent microcontrollers are often integrated with on-chip debug circuitry that when accessed by an in-circuit emulator (ICE) via JTAG, allow debugging of the firmware with a debugger.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A real-time ICE may allow viewing and/or manipulating of internal states while running.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A tracing ICE can record executed program and MCU states before/after a trigger point.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Many others exist, some of which are used in very narrow range of applications or are more like applications processors than microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The microcontroller market is extremely fragmented, with numerous vendors, technologies, and markets.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Note that many vendors sell or have sold multiple architectures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In contrast to general-purpose computers, microcontrollers used in embedded systems often seek to optimize interrupt latency over instruction throughput.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Issues include both reducing the latency, and making it be more predictable (to support real-time control).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] When an electronic device causes an interrupt, during the context switch the intermediate results (registers) have to be saved before the software responsible for handling the interrupt can run.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] They must also be restored after that interrupt handler is finished.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] If there are more processor registers, this saving and restoring process may take more time, increasing the latency.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Another technique involves spending silicon gates on "shadow registers": One or more duplicate registers used only by the interrupt software, perhaps supporting a dedicated stack.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Lower end microcontrollers tend to support fewer interrupt latency controls than higher end ones.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Two different kinds of memory are commonly used with microcontrollers, a non-volatile memory for storing firmware and a read–write memory for temporary data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] From the earliest microcontrollers to today, six-transistor SRAM is almost always used as the read/write working memory, with a few more transistors per bit used in the register file.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] In addition to the SRAM, some microcontrollers also have internal EEPROM and/or NVRAM for data storage; and ones that do not have any (such as the BASIC Stamp), or where the internal memory is insufficient, are often connected to an external EEPROM or flash memory chip.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] A few microcontrollers beginning in 2003 have "self-programmable" flash memory.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] The earliest microcontrollers used mask ROM to store firmware.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Later microcontrollers (such as the early versions of the Freescale 68HC11 and early PIC microcontrollers) had EPROM memory, which used a translucent window to allow erasure via UV light, while production versions had no such window, being OTP (one-time-programmable).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Firmware updates were equivalent to replacing the microcontroller itself, thus many products were not upgradeable.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Motorola MC68HC805 was the first microcontroller to use EEPROM to store the firmware.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] EEPROM microcontrollers became more popular in 1993 when Microchip introduced PIC16C84 and Atmel introduced an 8051-core microcontroller that was first one to use NOR Flash memory to store the firmware.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/microcontroller] Today's microcontrollers almost all use flash memory, with a few models using FRAM and some ultra-low-cost parts still using OTP or mask ROM.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] A **watchdog timer** (**WDT**, or simply a **watchdog**), sometimes called a **computer operating properly timer** (**COP timer**), is an electronic or software timer that is used to detect and recover from computer malfunctions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are widely used in computers to facilitate automatic correction of temporary hardware faults, and to prevent errant or malevolent software from disrupting system operation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] During normal operation, the computer regularly restarts the watchdog timer to prevent it from elapsing, or *timing out*.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] If, due to a hardware fault or program error, the computer fails to restart the watchdog, the timer will elapse and generate a timeout signal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The timeout signal is used to initiate corrective actions.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The corrective actions typically include placing the computer and associated hardware in a safe state and invoking a computer reboot.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Microcontrollers often include an integrated, on-chip watchdog.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In other computers the watchdog may reside in a nearby chip that connects directly to the CPU, or it may be located on an external expansion card in the computer's chassis.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are commonly found in embedded systems and other computer-controlled equipment where humans cannot easily access the equipment or would be unable to react to faults in a timely manner.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In such systems, the computer cannot depend on a human to invoke a reboot if it hangs; it must be self-reliant.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, remote embedded systems such as space probes are not physically accessible to human operators; these could become permanently disabled if they were unable to autonomously recover from faults.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In robots and other automated machines, a fault in the control computer could cause equipment damage or injuries before a human could react, even if the computer is easily accessed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer is usually employed in cases like these.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are also used to monitor and limit software execution time on a normally functioning computer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, a watchdog timer may be used when running untrusted code in a sandbox, to limit the CPU time available to the code and thus prevent some types of denial-of-service attacks.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In real-time operating systems, a watchdog timer may be used to monitor a time-critical task to ensure it completes within its maximum allotted time and, if it fails to do so, to terminate the task safely and report the failure.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The act of restarting a watchdog timer is commonly referred to as *kicking* the watchdog.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In electronic watchdogs, kicking is typically done by writing to a watchdog control port or by setting a particular bit in a register.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Alternatively, some tightly coupled watchdog timers are kicked by executing a special machine language instruction.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] An example of this is the CLRWDT (clear watchdog timer) instruction found in the instruction set of some PIC microcontrollers.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In computers that are running operating systems, electronic watchdog restarts are usually invoked through a device driver.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, in the Linux operating system, a user space program will kick the watchdog by interacting with the watchdog device driver, typically by writing a zero character to /dev/watchdog or by calling a KEEPALIVE ioctl.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The device driver, which serves to abstract the watchdog hardware from user space programs, may also be used to configure the time-out period and start and stop the timer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some watchdog timers will only allow kicks during a specific time window.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The window timing is usually relative to the previous kick or, if the watchdog has not yet been kicked, to the moment the watchdog was enabled.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The window begins after a delay following the previous kick, and ends after a further delay.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] If the computer attempts to kick the watchdog before or after the window, the watchdog will not be restarted, and in some implementations this will be treated as a fault and trigger corrective action.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer is said to be *enabled* when operating and *disabled* when idle.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Upon power-up, a watchdog may be unconditionally enabled or it may be initially disabled and require an external signal to enable it.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In the latter case, the enabling signal may be automatically generated by hardware or it may be generated under software control.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] When automatically generated, the enabling signal is typically derived from the computer reset signal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In some systems the reset signal is directly used to enable the watchdog.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In others, the reset signal is delayed so that the watchdog will become enabled at some later time following the reset.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] This delay allows time for the computer to boot before the watchdog is enabled.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Without this delay, the watchdog would timeout and invoke a subsequent reset before the computer can run its application software — the software which kicks the watchdog — and the system would become stuck in an endless cycle of incomplete reboots.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers come in many configurations, and many allow their configurations to be altered.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, the watchdog and CPU may share a common clock signal as shown in the block diagram below, or they may have independent clock signals or in some cases the watchdog may have no clock signal at all.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Two or more timers are sometimes cascaded to form a *multistage watchdog timer*, where each timer is referred to as a *timer stage*, or simply a *stage*.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, the block diagram below shows a three-stage watchdog.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Depending on the design, this may be implemented with multiple timers, or by emulating multiple timers with a single timer and additional logic.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In a multistage watchdog, only the first stage is kicked by the processor.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Upon first stage timeout, a corrective action is initiated and the next stage in the cascade is started.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] As each subsequent stage times out, it triggers a corrective action and starts the next stage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Upon final stage timeout, a corrective action is initiated, but no other stage is started because the end of the cascade has been reached.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Typically, single-stage watchdog timers are used to simply restart the computer, whereas multistage watchdog timers will sequentially trigger a series of corrective actions, with the final stage triggering a computer restart.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers may have either fixed or programmable time intervals.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some watchdog timers allow the time interval to be programmed by selecting from among a few selectable, discrete values.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In others, the interval can be programmed to arbitrary values.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Typically, watchdog time intervals range from ten milliseconds to a minute or more.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In a multistage watchdog, each timer may have its own, unique time interval.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer may initiate any of several types of corrective action, including maskable interrupt, non-maskable interrupt, hardware reset, fail-safe state activation, power cycling, or combinations of these.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Depending on its architecture, the type of corrective action or actions that a watchdog can trigger may be fixed or programmable.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some computers (e.g., PC compatibles) require a pulsed signal to invoke a hardware reset.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In such cases, the watchdog typically triggers a hardware reset by activating an internal or external pulse generator, which in turn creates the required reset pulses.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In embedded systems and control systems, watchdog timers are often used to activate fail-safe circuitry.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] When activated, the fail-safe circuitry forces all control outputs to safe states (e.g., turns off motors, heaters, and high-voltages) to prevent injuries and equipment damage while the fault persists.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In a two-stage watchdog, the first timer is often used to activate fail-safe outputs and start the second timer stage; the second stage will reset the computer if the fault cannot be corrected before the timer elapses.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are sometimes used to trigger the recording of system state information—which may be useful during fault recovery—or debug information (which may be useful for determining the cause of the fault) onto a persistent medium.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In such cases, a second timer—which is started when the first timer elapses—is typically used to reset the computer later, after allowing sufficient time for data recording to complete.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] This allows time for the information to be saved, but ensures that the computer will be reset even if the recording process fails.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, the above diagram shows a likely configuration for a two-stage watchdog timer.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] During normal operation the computer regularly kicks Stage1 to prevent a timeout.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] If the computer fails to kick Stage1 (e.g., due to a hardware fault or programming error), Stage1 will eventually timeout.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] This event will start the Stage2 timer and, simultaneously, notify the computer (by means of a non-maskable interrupt) that a reset is imminent.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Until Stage2 times out, the computer may attempt to record state information, debug information, or both.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] As a last resort, the computer will be reset upon Stage2 timeout.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] A watchdog timer provides automatic detection of catastrophic malfunctions that prevent the computer from kicking it.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] However, computers can have other, less-severe types of faults which do not interfere with kicking, but which still require watchdog oversight.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] To support these, a computer system is typically designed so that its watchdog timer will be kicked only if the computer deems the system functional.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The computer determines whether the system is functional by conducting one or more fault detection tests and will kick the watchdog only if all tests have passed.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In computers that are running an operating system and multiple processes, a single, simple test might be insufficient to guarantee normal operation, as it could fail to detect a subtle fault condition and consequently kick the watchdog even though a fault condition exists.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, in the case of the Linux operating system, a user-space watchdog daemon may simply kick the watchdog periodically without performing any tests.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] As long as the daemon runs normally, the system will be protected against serious system crashes such as a kernel panic.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Upon discovery of a failed test, the computer may attempt to perform a sequence of corrective actions under software control, culminating with a software-initiated reboot.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] If the software fails to invoke a reboot, the hardware watchdog timer — if available — will timeout and invoke a hardware reset.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In effect, this is a multistage watchdog timer in which the software comprises the first and the hardware WDT the final stage.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In a Linux system, for example, the watchdog daemon can be configured to attempt to perform a software-initiated reboot, which may be preferable to a hardware reset as it allows file systems to be safely unmounted and fault information to be logged prior to the reboot.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] It is essential, however, to have the insurance provided by a hardware WDT, to allow for the case in which a fault causes the daemon itself to malfunction, and thus become unable to invoke a reboot.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Watchdog timers are implemented in various ways.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some electronic WDTs (e.g., Analog Devices MAX6324) use linear timing circuits that operate without a digital clock signal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Other electronic WDTs, and software WDTs, typically employ digital counters as timers and rely on a clock signal for proper operation.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Electronic WDTs are usually implemented either as a stand-alone integrated circuit (IC) or as part of a more complex IC.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some stand-alone implementations contain only a WDT, whereas others bundle a WDT with other functions (e.g. supply voltage supervisors) in a common IC.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Many microcontrollers have a watchdog "module" consisting of a digital WDT and mechanisms for controlling and monitoring the WDT.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Such modules typically include related control and status registers, circuitry for qualifying restart triggers ("kicks"), and routing control logic for the timeout signal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some microcontrollers provide an analog WDT in lieu of a digital WDT.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, Texas Instruments' TMS470 microcontroller has an analog WDT that employs an external capacitor and resistor to program the watchdog interval.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In microcontrollers and other complex digital ICs, a digital WDT is typically instantiated by synthesizing it from a description written in VHDL, Verilog or some other hardware description language.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Analog WDTs have a *kick* input and *timeout* output, but lack the clock input signal found in digital electronic watchdogs.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Circuitry and components vary widely among analog watchdogs, but in general, analog WDTs typically base their timing functions on capacitor charging rates.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, in the analog watchdog circuit shown to the right, electric current *i* gradually charges capacitor *C*, causing voltage *VC* to ramp up (rise at a constant rate).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In normal operation, periodic "kick" pulses are applied to the kick input.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Each kick causes capacitor *C* to discharge, thus restarting the voltage ramp-up.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] However, if the kicks cease or become spaced too far apart in time, *VC* will rise above the voltage comparator's threshold voltage *VTH* and, as a result, the voltage comparator will assert the *timeout* signal.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Some software watchdog timers are implemented as standard software modules.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Examples of these include "Softdog", a virtual device driver which emulates an electronic WDT and conforms to the Linux watchdog API, and MathWorks' Software Watchdog Timer, a retriggerable one-shot timer which can be instantiated by dragging its GUI representation onto a block diagram.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Other software WDTs are typically custom-designed to meet specific requirements.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Every software WDT depends on a timing reference to allow it to accurately track the passage of time.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Various mechanisms are commonly available for this purpose.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] Depending on the computer, and if used, the operating system (OS), such mechanisms may include programmable interval timers, kernel timers, the system clock, and synchronization objects (e.g., semaphores) that support timed waits.
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] For example, in bare metal applications (program running without an OS), timing references are often limited to programmable interval timers (PIT).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] In the above example, if the application program fails to kick the watchdog (by restarting the PIT), the PIT will reach the end of the watchdog interval and generate an interrupt request (IRQ).
[src:watchdog-timer-design/watchdog-timer] The associated interrupt service routine (ISR) will then execute and take corrective action via programmed I/O, system calls, or other software-controlled operations.
